  <main class="container" role="main">
    <header>
      <div class="logo">GIT</div>
      <div>
        <h1>The History of Git</h1>
        <p class="lead">A concise 500-word narrative about how Git started, why it mattered, and how it grew into the backbone of modern software development.</p>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="hero" aria-labelledby="intro">
      <div class="flex">
        <div class="col">
          <article id="intro">
            <p style="margin:0;color:#dff7ea;">In 2005, when the Linux kernel community needed a fast, distributed version control system they could trust, Linus Torvalds created Git. The immediate trigger was the kernel project's fallout with a proprietary system they had briefly adopted. Torvalds designed Git to be small, fast, and to support non-linear workflows at massive scale — emphasizing integrity, performance, and a model that treats every developer as a potential maintainer.</p>
            <p style="margin-top:12px;color:var(--muted)">Git’s name was chosen with a wink — "git" being British slang for an unpleasant person — but its design was deliberate. Several core ideas defined Git: snapshots instead of changesets, content-addressable storage using SHA-1 (later migrated to stronger hashes), local commits enabling offline work, and cheap branching and merging that encouraged experimentation. These ideas made workflows like feature-branching and pull requests practical.</p>
          </article>
        </div>
        <div class="col" aria-hidden="true">
          <svg width="100%" height="100%" viewBox="0 0 300 200" preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet" style="max-height:180px">
            <defs>
              <linearGradient id="g" x1="0" x2="1"><stop offset="0" stop-color="#7c3aed"/><stop offset="1" stop-color="#06b6d4"/></linearGradient>
            </defs>
            <rect x="0" y="0" width="300" height="200" rx="12" fill="url(#g)" opacity="0.12"></rect>
            <g transform="translate(24,36) scale(1)">
              <circle cx="16" cy="24" r="8" fill="#fff" opacity="0.9"></circle>
