              <rect x="8" y="72" width="160" height="56" rx="8" fill="#fff" opacity="0.06"></rect>
            </g>
          </svg>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="timeline" aria-label="timeline">
      <div class="event">
        <h3>2005 — Birth of Git</h3>
        <div class="meta">Linus Torvalds, created to replace BitKeeper after licensing disputes.</div>
        <p style="margin-top:8px;color:var(--muted)">Torvalds released the first Git in April 2005. The initial goals were simplicity, speed, and robust support for distributed workflows. Early development focused on kernel workflows: high-volume branching, rebasing, and merging across many contributors.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="event">
        <h3>2005–2007 — Growth and Community</h3>
        <div class="meta">Rapid adoption by open-source projects.</div>
        <p style="margin-top:8px;color:var(--muted)">Developers and projects quickly embraced Git because it solved real pain points. Tools and hosting services began to appear, and the community improved documentation, GUIs, and integrations that lowered the learning curve.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="event">
        <h3>2008 — GitHub and Social Collaboration</h3>
        <div class="meta">Git meets the web.</div>
        <p style="margin-top:8px;color:var(--muted)">GitHub launched in 2008, combining Git with social features like pull requests, forking, and web-based reviews. This catalyzed collaboration patterns that are now industry standards and made Git accessible to millions.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="event">
        <h3>2010s — Maturation and Ecosystem</h3>
        <div class="meta">Tooling, GUIs, and enterprise adoption.</div>
        <p style="margin-top:8px;color:var(--muted)">Throughout the 2010s, Git’s ecosystem matured: graphical tools, continuous integration, and enterprise hosting became common. Platforms like GitLab, Bitbucket, and managed services broadened adoption in corporate settings.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="event">
        <h3>Recent Years — Security and Scale</h3>
        <div class="meta">Hash upgrades and wider use.</div>
        <p style="margin-top:8px;color:var(--muted)">Git has evolved to address security and scale, moving away from SHA-1 toward stronger hashing and improving performance for very large repositories. It remains the foundation of modern software development workflows worldwide.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

